text: In general, this looks like an interesting movie. Despite an abundance of product placement and self-promotion, there does seem to be some creativity and effort put into how the internet is depicted (but is it just me, or has The Emoji Movie tainted this concept a little?). I just hope it has at least one reference to Tron, and perhaps a cameo from Jack Sparrow.    What bothers me though is some of the self-parodying that the princesses do. Sure, they do reference the most stereotypical themes associated with themselves, and feel cleverly used as Jonas Brothers-esque performers, but other than that it feels a bit disrespectful. Not as much to the characters as to the people who in the earlier days of Disney helped create them. Snow White, for instance, is a character that has admittedly aged, but from a seniority point of view, she should feel a bit more dignified. She was the very first Disney princess after all, in the first feature-length animated movie ever. And as much as I enjoy that Disney are willing to make fun of themselves, didn't they already do that with Enchanted? Also, do they really need to hammer the point of feminism in when they already have characters like Elsa, Mulan and Belle present?   I also have a fear that Wreck-it Ralph 2, like a lot of movies right now, will lean too heavily on nostalgia in order to sell itself to an audience. Admittedly it did the same with videogame characters in the first one, but the references it made fit the mold of the story and didn't distract from our main characters. Because Ralph and Vanellope seems to be out of their element for most of the movie, the risk of the movie feeling like a huge sidetrack might be higher.  Though I'm not gonna jump the gun yet and say that this will be stupid, cause I do like some of the stuff I've seen here. The Disney-princesses look pretty good in this format, and some of their other characteristics are cleverly used, like how Pocahontas hair appears to have a constant breeze in it, or that Cinderella uses her glass slipper like a broken bottle.

text: You know, I don't even have to predict that its going to be a gigantic billion dollar box office hit. I don't don't even have to predict that will have a high rating on rotten tomatoes. Hell, I don't even have to predict that it will win an Academy Award for Best Animated Feature. Because this entire movie just speaks for itself. Never have I laughed so hard at a movie that would not only be better than the original, but also more exciting than the original too. I guess I could see it in theaters and have a fun time seeing it. This movie might even be one of my favs. Though I really do hope that they only feature the Disney Princesses in one scene and not for the entire movie, otherwise it overhype its audience even further. But still, funny, laughable, suprising, great visuals, and tuns of humor, Ralph breaks the internet is going to be a feel good to watch movie that I will hail as a masterpiece. I still can't believe they featured the Princesses in one scene.

text: Some people may argue against the comment Rapunzel makes but she is correct. It is a bit of a misconception for the most part in regards to the Disney Princess movies.   When you analyze the films more, at most I would say Aurora, Jasmine, and kind of Snow White had their problems solved from a male. To be fair to Snow White, she is about 14, and her problems were solved with the help of multiple male adults, such as the hunter, the dwarves, then finally the prince.  Oh, and Ariel too I suppose since Prince Eric defeats Ursula in the end although her problems weren't "solved" until her father granted her legs.   Cinderella's problems were solved due to a fairy Godmother and deciding to rebel, and then coincidentally falling in love.  Tiana and Rapunzel were a strange set of partnered circumstances that were originally mutual agreements between both parties that are helping each other and then a conflict with Dr. Facilier and Mother Gothel. Pocahontas actually gained problems due to John and the other colonists searching for gold. And we certainly can't include Mulan, Merrida, Anna, Elsa, or Alice in not solving their problems.  Moana had some prophecy stuff to get Maui and mostly saves the day herself.   It's kind of strange that Disney has this reputation in regards to their Princess films as they really aren't like that at all for the most part. Perhaps due to marketing, toys, etc and particularly from past Disney which was founded in the 20s but not the actual movies. Sorry my comment was so long and I was still trying to be thorough while keeping it short! ^-^

For me, it just made it harder to read or write. I started working really hard on how to read better. My family helped me by making me read everything from menus, to cereal boxes, to road signs. text: So Disney is just going to go through and destroy all it's proprieties again? 1:37 that's not how those (most of) Princesses would react they're not fighters.  Especially the classic ones, Snow white, Cinderella, Aurora, it's very out of character for them. But instead of having the more feisty/worrier princesses stand at the ready  and the more gentile and meek ones hide they just made them all jump up.  All of these charterers are established and the original ones were very sincere and now they make them all porridge. Now they've made them milk toast just blandly strong, knowing, and independent Which takes away the uniqueness of the ones who were always like that.  Let's not forget that the men who saved them (if you really want to take it that literally)  are all very good and great men. For goodness sake Aurora's "Big strong man" slayed a dragon and woke her from eternal sleep.  You'd have to be a little thick to take fairy tails literally but they will. But even if you do that, how can you possibly think that "a big strong man" is a bad thing? As if having a good, strong, brave man around would be a bad or demeaning thing. Or that being so good, kind, hard working, pure, and loving that you inspire someone to take up arms and defend you when you're too weak to do anything ( because of the multiple assassination attempts) is wrong.  O.K. I'm starting to cool down and I know I shouldn't condemn a move based on a 2 minuet  trailer. I know that is kind of what I'm doing.  For those of you how made it through the dark times that were the Cinderella straight to DVD sequels you will understand why I'm so defensive.  It hurts when you see the characters you love and grew up with changed to fit with the agenda of the month attitude. I've seen this happen to those who love star wars  and saw the prequels and were hurt and now the new ones, oi va. I actually don't know about Star Wars that's just what I've been seeing. Which Disney also owns now... hmm.  Wow I didn't think my comment would get this long.  I guess this isn't really about Wreck-It Ralph more on the whole princess zeitgeist as is stands. I hope this was just an overreaction by me and the move is good but I'm weary of sequels.  Well thanks for reading this maybe if you feel the way I do you enjoyed this supper long comment. <3 -Lily   P.S. the classic princesses look really bad with the new CGI.

I have nothing against social justice but I hate when it's blatantly rubbed in my face just to appeal to people before they make a hash tag that needlessly destroys a franchise. Seriously, you never see Mulan stop in the middle of the story to make a speech about being a strong woman while slipping in a line about Disney's new movies. I look at this trailer and I don't see a team of passionate writers, I see fifty people in business suits deciding where to slip in the next star wars reference and then deciding not to subtlety slip it in but have Ralph scream "I Love Star Wars Because It Has Strong Female Characters." I know some people think it's just a kids movie but I'm wanted to rant a bit after seeing that. Hope other people understand where I'm coming from.

I‚Äôm not roasting film/game theory but sometimes rather than acting like you are hiding what you know until the end of the video to create some suspense, it‚Äôs better to lay out the differences between the two while still explaining why it IS ‚Äúokay‚Äù. Sorry, I‚Äôve just noticed this is how a lot of his theories go. In my mind he should start doing diet theories again. He only did one of these (As far as I know but am pretty sure) and it helped to crunch a reasonable theory into a short amount of time. text: I REALLY wanna like this movie, but I hate this trailer more every time I watch it.   0:00 No reason given for WHY they're going to the internet, just... what I assume was supposed to be a joke?   0:53 Dated joke where we aren't even told what they're looking for.   1:18 This part was kinda funny, but we still have no idea what ANY of it has to do with the story.   2:08 Really? You named your whole movie that just for one lamp shading joke? Lamp shading only works if you somehow subvert the trope you're lamp shading! Also, I hate these millennial consultant characters: older people don't get them, younger people feel unjustifiably insulted by them, and the only people in on the joke are the people that made the movie! They aren't fun, they aren't likable, and every minute they're on screen is another minute you want them to go away.  Just watch the trailer for the original movie again if you wanna see how product placement and nostalgic pandering can be funny AND seamlessly integrated into the story in only two minutes.

text: People are saying that this film is just seems it's gonna 'end up like the emoji movie'. This is just my opinion on the matter. Let's look at the facts:  This is a Disney Animation film, which hopefully means it won't need too much advertising, since Disney don't need it. Sure it has things like twitter, amazon and google shown on it. But that's because it's the internet. Those are 3 of the biggest names on it, of course they are gonna be featured. It wouldn't be the internet without it. Also the search bar guy could have easily been Google. The other companies were only shown for a second maybe two each. The biggest advertisement was for Disney and other companies it owns. The emoji movie was also a film based off emoji's, a really dumb concept when you think about. I haven't watched it because I've never wanted to but I know enough about it that it doesn't make sense. (Is their a thing as a 'just dance' app?)  This is a sequel to a successful film that will expand the world for characters people already know and like. Plus it's the same director and one of the same writers as the first one, so they should know what they are doing.  Other opinions:  Sure they advertised other companies Disney owns. But this is the sequel to a film which had several game characters from different franchises on the same screen. Of course they are gonna do the same thing again with stuff Disney owns. It's it character for what they did in the first one. Honestly, I find it great that they did. Seeing a X-Wing, Iron Man, EVE and Kermit on the same screen was something I never saw coming.  I knew from a news thing awhile back that they were gonna do the princess thing so I'm not shocked they put it in the trailer. But honestly, I find how they did it hilarious. And I like the fact that they got the princesses respective actresses to reprise their roles (except ones who have passed away). I'm pretty sure it's gonna be for that one scene though.  When I first saw the title for this film, I thought it was gonna be a bit weird. But now, I think this is gonna be a really good film and I'm really excited about watching it.

text: I honestly can't see this movie being any good. People keep saying its gonna be like the emoji movie but better. All I say its gonna end up just like the emoji movie. Wreck it Ralph was such a good movie because it was a story of trying to fit in, while adding references to 80s pop culture. This movie just seems to be attempting to market Disney and to fit as many references to pop culture as it can into the movie. The reasons I feel this movie will be bad are  1.  From this trailer, this movie will most likely have a shallow plot wit the basis of saving the internet.   2.  It will most likely not have any character development considering we got all the development that was possible between Ralp and Candy girl  3. The amount of pop culture references of today's society basically just sjows this movie is going to pander to Kids and is going to have jokes that just fall flat.  The 1st movie was so good because we got to see such good development between all the characters in the movie. The movie also ended on a satisfying note with Ralph and candy girl becoming happy with their lives. There was really no point in making a second movie and its obvious that this movie was made just to cash out on the popularity of the 1st one.

text: This seriously looks brilliant. I love the trailer, although I have to point out that this is yet another Disney movie that somehow forgets to include Megara in the Princess line up - well, she's married to a demigod instead of a Prince - but come on! Hercules is one of the best Disney films ever made; it has the best villain, incredible songs from Alan Menkin and Megara, the first, truly independent female role. She comes from nothing, sells her soul to the devil to save her boyfriend's (Achilles) life, who then cheats on her and still she manages to pull her life together. Surely that should be a good enough reason to include more of her? I know, I know, Hercules wasn't as popular as all the other films the Princesses shown in Ralph 2 were and there would be a real uproar if Elsa was without Anna (or would there be?), but these Princesses get all the screen time in all the movies and wouldn't it be great to bring some of the others in from time-to-time? Like Kida from Atlantis who is definitely a Princess (another amazing film) or Esmeralda from Hunchback who is definitely not a Princess but comes from a film which has the most breathtaking score. And wouldn't it be great to introduce these characters to a new generation who will then go back and watch the films and realise how amazing they are? Frozen was and still is the most successful and popular Disney film of all time, but that doesn't make it the best Disney film of all time. You put it alongside Beauty and the Beast, Aladdin or Hercules - it still stands up as one of the greats, but not the greatest. Of course you need to keep bringing Elsa and Anna into the mix as they are still relevant, but you're Disney. If you can make an arcade game from almost 40 years ago relevant again, surely you can do the same for some of your "forgotten" Princesses? I know I'm rambling and probably sounding like a proper geek, but I'm proud of being a geek and a huge Disney fanboy. I may be in my 30s now, but Disney appeals to all ages and let's us all know that it's ok to appease our inner child. There are 56 animated Disney movies with most having either a Princess or a strong female lead. As we are all born at different times, we all have our favourites and it would be great if they could all seen again, from time to time.

text: I'm seeing people say stuff about the "modern feminist agenda" but I've seen articles going back to the 1990s that complained about this common, reoccurring trope. This sort of outlook on Disney films isn't exactly a new thing guys, so chill out. If anything, this is Disney poking fun at themselves, which (to me at least) is perfectly fine.  Also, people have been comparing it to The Emoji Movie, and yes, the concepts are similar, but really, the closest thing to "Good" that came out of that train-wreck was the idea of exploring the Internet and social media in the modern era, and since the aforementioned train-wreck misused that potential, I'd say that a second round from a much more competent company is at least worth a shot.  Anyway, I'm looking forward to this movie, and look forward to seeing Disney poke fun at their history. Honestly though, I'd burst out laughing if they referenced Song of the South in this thing.

text: 1:55 This doesn't make any sense. The only time I've ever heard people assume that all the princess' problems were solved by a man was when they actually were like in the case of both Sleeping Beauty and Snow White. If it weren't for the men showing up they would be dead. The other cases are as follows:  Cinderella: Her Fairy Godmother and a bunch of animals solved her problems. Beauty and the Beat: Big strong man caused the problem and everyone acknowledges this  Aladdin: The movie wasn't about Jasmine, but really the Genie solved everyone's issues Pocahontas: I don't actually know since whenever anyone talks about it its about how horribly inaccurate and bad the movie is  The Little Mermaid: Ursula would have killed Ariel if Eric handed rammed a boat into her. Triton gives her legs to be with Eric. I don't actually think she solves a single one of her problems with her own power. Mulan: Mulan's the hero and no one is going to contest that Brave: Literally all about that not being the case Princess and the Frog: Never saw it and nobody ever talks about it so I don't know (honestly it feels like people forgot it existed) Tangled: Rapunzel saved herself with some assistance from Flynn Frozen: The same as Beauty and the Beast Moana: Moana saved the day, Maui helped Wreck-it-Ralph: If Ralph hadn't fixed Venellope's code she would be dead (The scene in the new movie makes her look like an ingrate)  Taking all of this into account, the joke takes on a whole different meaning than the one I think is intended. I think the joke is just supposed to be that princesses aren't given enough credit and are constantly being overshadowed, but honestly what I get from the joke is that the princesses are just being self-deprecating. It's kind of sad thinking that these character think that they're not given the credit they deserve, but it's also really strange given that they are wildly more popular than the men in their stories. (I don't remember the names of either of the princes from Snow White or Sleeping Beauty at all)  A side note: Why is Mulan with the princesses? She's not a princess. And where's Kida from Atlantis? She actually was a princess, but she's not included? Oh wait, that's right, that movie wasn't popular enough...

The first one had product placement, but they always made something out of it, like the nesquick sand and the oreos. This is literally just product placement. Straight outta the emoji movie.   Well hopefully the story is good, but I'm gonna keep my hopes down for this one.

text: frankly i feel the "big strong man" joke is kinda funny, but isn't exactly warranted. i can sort of understand where it comes from, but when you actually think about it, only a few of those Disney Princesses are even in a scenario where you could argue "big strong man came in to solve all the damsel's problems". -Jasmine didn't have any serious problems that weren't actually caused by alladin(if the genie never showed up everything would have been business as usual with no schemes plots or giant hour-glasses) -Rapunzel worked just as hard as Eugene (and the horse) to solve her problems, so it's kind of silly to say that about her story -Elsa and Anna should be an obvious no. The main male characters were 1: an antagonist and 2: just sort of along for the ride -I can hardly remember the little mermaid or pocahontas, but as far as i can gather, neither ariel nor pocahontas would have even had any problems to solve if their love interest didn't exist.  -Merida is a no because that's kind of the entire point of Brave as a movie.. -I never watched the princess and the frog movie, but i think she turns into a frog, which seems like the opposite of solving problems, to me. also, it's a frog, not a big strong man. i think -No clue about Moana, still haven't gotten around to seeing it -Belle's only problem before the movie began was Gaston, and i don't think the beast did belle any favors tbh. unless you count stockholm syndrome as a plus? -You can make this argument for snow white and (the original) sleeping beauty, because they were basically in comas until their future love interest kissed em awake -and you can also make the argument for cinderella, but while it's true her prince searched for her and found her and whisked her away from practical slavery at the hands of her stepmother, you also need to consider that none of it could have been possible without cinderella having the courage and gall to actually go to the ball in the first place   honestly the bigger meta joke to take away from most of these disney movies is that magic does absolutely nothing but ruin these girls' lives....  anybody disagree, or?

Yet, many people will still discount God and His goodness even when shown evidence that the Bible is valid and coming true. A lot of people have difficulty believing in God because of all the evils in the world. However, this discounting of the only Person who can save you may be less of an inborn frustration or complaint and more of a hidden longing, placed there by the very One who planted His own image into the body and soul of every person He created. Where does this deep-seated intuition that suffering and pain are not right come from if we're just amalgamations of atoms, as the atheists say‚Ä¶?  What if, perhaps, this intuition points to something deeper? Something built into ourselves that reflects our true nature and identity? What if this revulsion against suffering and pain is a reminder of paradise, on one hand, and an anticipation of New Jerusalem on the other?  Perhaps it's the cry of the human spirit for God. For our Creator. The only One who can, and will, fix this mess.  As I've said, time is short. Bible Prophecy is happening at a frightening pace. You could argue, "You're just being paranoid like all the other fundamentalists. Haven't we always had these types of problems?" Sure... But never at this magnitude or frequency! Check the news for yourselves. The amount of earthquakes, bloodshed, madness and horrific weather events are off the charts! Don't be deceived into thinking it's not as bad as it seems out there. The devil wants you to stay anemic and apathetic. Don't let that jerk deceive you. Or win your soul. Satan wants nothing more than for you to roll your eyes, scoff under your breath and put this whole "God" business under the rug. He wants you to continue believing that Hell and God and the afterlife is nonsense. That the Bible is all fairy tale nonsense of Jesus riding dinosaurs; that it's stuff only the weak-minded, brainwashed people believe. He'll gladly coax your pride, making you believe you're far too "reasoned" to believe in such things. However, Satan believes the Bible. Every jot and word of it. He doesn't see it as fairy-tale nonsense since it details his coming destruction. He just doesn't want YOU to believe it so he can drag your soul down with him when it's time for him to go!  Don't let him drag you down into the grave with him. Don't be played! Hell is a very real place-- a place of eternal separation, loneliness, and despair. No friends, no family... just you. A-L-O-N-E. In the dark. Miserable for all eternity. If hell wasn't real, what on earth was Jesus willing to die for to protect us from...? Bill Nye thinks hell won't be so bad; he claims he's willing to hold onto his darwinian beliefs even if it means he's hellbound for it. I hope you won't share in that kind of disillusioned thinking...  Before you're sent to hell, you'll appear at the Great White Throne Judgment. Whether you believe in hell or not makes no difference--that giant throne you want to avoid seeing at all costs will be your destiny if Christ isn't your Savior. At the Great White Throne Judgment the books are thrown wide open and the past is recalled. Details and sins long forgotten or covered up are brought to light. Plenty of people will have a list of good deeds: acts of charity, love, and sacrifice. All their good deeds will be carefully considered... but none of them will be good enough to gain them admittance into heaven. The good deeds they did will have an impact on where they end up in the lake of fire, however. Hell will not be the same for everyone, but it will still be eternal misery... misery you could have easily avoided.  Sinners will wish they had done just a little less evil so their punishment could be a little more tolerable. Pornographers will wish they hadn't made so many videos. Control freaks will wish they hadn't been so angry and abusive. The internet troll will wish he hadn't cursed and slung so many demeaning insults toward a stranger online. And the abortionist will wish they hadn't killed any pre-born infants. All sins will be exposed. There's no way out... unless...  Unless you accept Christ as your Savior. Confess that you're a sinner, repent of your sins and accept His free gift of salvation and grace. It's all yours... free for the taking! Jesus is the only way to get out of what's coming soon upon this world. I know you've probably heard "Jesus loves you" a million times in your life, and it probably sounds like an empty mantra by now... but it really is the truth! Do you know why you exist? Have you ever stopped and pondered about that...? Nothing in this life comes to be without God's approval first. That means that God thought¬† you were so worth the effort that He created you!  Or maybe you're wondering, "How do I know that only Jesus can save me? What about Islam? Or what about Hinduism or Buddhism? How do I know that the Bible isn't a book of fiction and myths? In fact, what about all the starving kids in Africa? If God is so "just and loving," explain that one!" These are incredibly valid questions that deserve real answers. In fact, how can you even know God is real to begin with?  If you have deep questions related to God, or if you're just remotely curious about Him... I encourage you to search out these authors. I'll even list some of their books that address just about any issue or question you could have about God:  Frank Turek- "Stealing From God: Why Atheists Need God to Make Their Case"  Andreas Kostenberger- "Truth Matters"  Louis Markos- "Apologetics for the 21st Century"  Norman L. Geisler- "When Skeptics Ask," "I Don't Have Enough Faith To Be An Atheist"  C.S. Lewis- "Mere Christianity"  Lee Strobel- "The Case For Christ," "The Case For A Creator," "The Case For Grace"  Ravi Zacharias- "The End of Reason," "Jesus Among Other Gods," "Can Man Live Without God?" "Why Suffering?"  Philip Yancey- "Reaching For The Invisible God," "Disappointment With God"  Also, the "One Minute Apologist" right here on YouTube offers quick videos that tackle tough questions about God.  **  Why am I telling you all this? Especially when this has absolutely nothing to do with the video you're watching? Simple: to warn you. To offer you a life line. Deep down, if you have discernment and common sense, you can tell something is dreadfully wrong with this world and something in your heart is telling you to get right with God before it's too late. Don't ignore that voice! Listen to it, no matter how small it is. I'm just a beggar telling other beggars where they can go to find the Bread of Life.  Don't let anything stop you from finding God. To quote Erwin Lutzer: "Standing at the Great White Throne Judgment will be hordes from every country of the world, from every religion in the world, with the best intentions in the world. They will learn too late that God is serious about justice, and if Christ does not bear their punishment, they must bear their own."  Don't lose your life! Let Christ save you while there's still time.

text: Sure, the feminist joke at the end is amusing, but in light of Tangled, Frozen, and Moana, all of which feature strong, independent women, it doesn't make sense. Yes, the men take a hand in helping the princesses save the day, but the princesses are not reliant on the men (not in the way they were in classic Disney films). Rapunzel saves Flynn just as much as he saves her. Anna saves Elsa. Moana recognizes that the fire demon is the goddess without a heart. This joke seems to suggest that strong men should be absent from Disney princess films. I just think that's sad.

text: Sigh.....another modern movie where all the male characters are either stupid buffoons or sarcastic emoqueers. I realized a while ago that part of the appeal of superhero movies today is that the main characters were created in the 60s or 70s so modern screenwriters can't turn them into faggots without seriously damaging the content. In the end, it's really such a simple concept: "write good characters, don't write bad characters".   Look at Batman for example. Batman is awesome. Why? Batman is awesome because he's a man. If Batman was a sissy, he wouldn't be awesome. Now I challenge anyone to name one male non-sissy character in a modern non-superhero movie. You can't because there aren't any and they're all lame. None of them are cool. Ever since the Illumiscum started pushing their emasculation agenda, Hollywood writers started trying to eliminate the good, masculine, male character from movies so now they're all sissy faggots and emoqueers. If Samuel L. Jackson was trying to make a name for himself today, he wouldn't be able to because his role doesn't exist anymore and that would be a shame because Samuel L. Jackson is a damn good actor.  The first Wreck-it Ralph was actually quite good because, although it had some feminist tropes, it didn't over-do it to the point of obnoxiousness. This one I think will probably be _aight_ too because it has some things working in its favor: the little girl is still cute and likeable, the movie looks good from an artistic standpoint, the plot is creative and original, and some of the jokes are actually funny. Likeable characters, good artwork, creativity, and humor; all tried and tested formulas for making a good animated movie that have and will continue going forward into the future to stand the passage-of-time.   But you have to wonder sometimes where this is all heading. Are the Hollywood Illumiscum trying to ruin entertainment forever and will they succeed in their nefariousness? Only those of us who are around long enough will see, I suppose.

text: Okay for that bit at 1:55, it's not the fact that they made a feminist joke that bothers me, it's more that the joke feels like such a lazy cheap shot and really doesn't make complete sense. "Do people assume all your problems were solved cause a big strong man showed up?" Snow White, Aurora, Ariel, Jasmine, Rapunzel and Vanellope all 6 of them had direct help from a man who, and let's be fair here, made a huge difference in their lives. This jab makes it sound as if the men made absolutely no difference and they could have just solved their problems themselves. Now I appreciate I'm probably reading wayyy too deep into this which is fair (that is a habit of mine :P ) but the fact is I've laughed at feminist jokes and this one just came off as a really lousy attempt by Disney to sound current.

text: Time to roast the feminists in this movie:  Rapunzel, You're certainly one to talk, considering the fact that you-and about EVERY SINGLE OTHER PRINCESS IN THIS ROOM got their problems solved because a big strong man showed up(AND I DON'T CARE IF THIS IS JUST DISNEY POKING FUN AT ITSELF).  Let's start with Cinderella, shall we? When you went to the ball, you immediately caught the eye of Prince Charming, and if he hadn't become so obsessed with your beauty and finding you to be his wife, you'd still be a slave at the hands of those three egotistical ----- -------- you call your stepfamily.  How about Belle? Granted she is probably one of the most intelligent of you lot, but the only difference here is that your problem WAS a big strong man showing up(Gaston). And it was only solved when another big strong man (The Beast) and you met up and realized that true beauty is found within and blah blah blah.  Snow White's story? When the evil queen showed up disguised as an old hag and put you into euthanasia with a poisoned apple, it was up to your very own prince to wake you up with true love's kiss. And considering the fact that you were practically singing "Someday My Prince Will Come" throughout the ENTIRETY of your movie, there is no chance in hell you can claim the mantle of "independent woman".  Then there's Rapunzel. In the original story, you were found by (Guess again) ANOTHER prince for whom you let down your hair. And after you were cast off in god knows where, the prince, though blinded, was the one who found you due to your singing voice. In Tangled, if it wasn't for that thief Eugene Fitzherbert, you would still be gleefully ignorant locked away by Mother Gothel. Heck, I don't even know why I call her "Mother", she is a mother to the devil only.  Next up is Moana. She could have NEVER restored the heart of Te Fiti on her own. She needed the help of Maui, who although was the reason this problem existed in the first place, was a key part in solving this problem. And though you say you're simply the daughter of the chief, I tend to agree with the Rock on your true status.  Anna...sweet naive pitiful Anna. The fact that your father locked you and your sister away for thirteen years should have driven you both insane. It's wonder why you weren't. But even after Elsa revealed her powers, it was Kristoff who took you up the North Mountain to get her down.  Pocahontas, you're not actually a princess-but your problems in the movie were partly solved by a man, namely John Smith. And whether or not you stood in the way of your father's mace as part of some ritual of goodwill or whether you truly did love him, proves you are everything BUT independent.  Even Tiana doesn't count for this, because although she DID work her butt off to raise money to open her own restaurant, the final push to achieve her dream came from Prince Navine.  And how about Ariel. Her vast curiosity was only sated after meeting Prince Eric, whom she went to great lengths to get her own set of legs to join him on land and eventually marry.  Then we have Merida. Now it's true she did attempt to take her marriage situation into her own hands by cheating the entire trial to find you a husband, but the clues of how to make things right with your mother came from the story of who? You guessed it, the story of a big strong man who let his pride get the better of him, but a big strong man nonetheless. In fact he wasn't just a big strong man, he was a big man with the strength of ten men.  Jasmine, your story is quite similar to Merida's, in that your parents both tried to force you to marry when you either didn't want to or hadn't found the right person. The difference here, is that a man DID show up, who happened to be a "street rat", but you ended up marrying him anyways, solving that problem and, alongside him, ridding your Sultanate of the villain Jafar once and for all.  And finally you, Vanellope. If it wasn't for Wreck-it Ralph, you'd still be trapped inside your own game and everyone would think that you are a glitch.  In fact, the only two people in this room who DIDN'T get their problems solved by a big strong man showing up are Elsa and Mulan, and they're not even Princesses at all!(one of them is a Queen and the other is not related to a royal family)

text: Overall, Ralph Breaks the Internet proves what most sequels desire to be ‚Äì it expands on the characters we have come to know and love while staying true to its roots of friendship and self-discovery. The stunning immensity of the Internet introduces plenty of ‚Äústicky situations‚Äù for Ralph and Vanellope to encounter, and this story takes us on a whimsical and faced-paced trip from the dark web to eBay. While Ralph is often presented as overly weak and insecure in comparison to his emotional strength in the finale of Wreck-it Ralph, Vanellope is able to find amazing self-growth throughout the film, and the two friends emerge ready to face the day. The works of Henry Jackman and Alan Menken serve to bring out ‚Äúthe feels‚Äù, while KnowsMore and the gang help to keep things light and hilarious. While not as refined as its predecessor, Ralph Breaks the Internet is a great addition to the Disney lineup, and I can‚Äôt wait to see what the future holds for Ralph and Vanellope.   To read my FULL REVIEW of Ralph Breaks the Internet, check out the link in my channel's bio!!!
